  "myth": {
    "title": "The Whispering Gods and the Dance of the Tribes",
    "text": "
    Long before the first fires of civilization flickered, when the world was still young and the tribes roamed like scattered leaves on the wind, the **First Voices** spoke from the shadows. They were not gods as we know them now—just whispers in the dark, half-remembered dreams, and the uneasy feeling that unseen eyes watched from the trees. The people of the time were few, their bands small, their lives hard. But the Voices grew louder with each generation, for they promised something precious: **meaning**.

    The first moralizing agents were weak—spirits of the hunt, ancestors who lingered, or the great beasts whose bones told stories of strength and sacrifice. A hunter who left an offering at a kill might return with more game; a woman who sang to the moon might bear a child. These were small things, but in a world of hunger and danger, small things mattered. The tribes that listened to the Voices, that performed the first clumsy rituals, survived a little longer. Their children grew, their bands swelled, and the Voices grew with them.

    Then came the **Great Speakers**—figures who claimed to hear the Voices clearly, who could call down blessings or curses with a word. They demanded more: not just offerings, but **faith**. A tribe that built a sacred fire and danced until dawn might see their enemies falter in battle. A people who painted their bodies with the signs of the Voices might find their women heavy with child, their men unbroken in war. The rituals became more potent, the beliefs more vivid. The Voices were no longer just whispers—they were **commands**, and disobedience brought misfortune.

    The tribes that embraced the Great Speakers grew mighty. They raided their neighbors, stole their women, and carried the Voices with them. Other tribes, seeing their strength, copied their rituals, their chants, their gods. Some changed the names, some twisted the stories, but the core remained: **obey, and you will endure**. The weak tribes faded. The strong tribes spread.

    And so the world filled with gods—jealous, generous, terrible, kind. They were not born all at once, but grew like vines, twisting around the needs of the people. Beliefs that began as accidents—fears of the dark, awe of the storm, the hope that a dead ancestor’s spirit might still watch over the living—became the foundations of great systems. The rituals that once soothed became **weapons**. The Voices that once whispered now **roared**, and the tribes that listened built empires.

    But the oldest truth remained, buried deep in the stories: the gods were never real. They were just the echoes of a desperate wish—**to matter**. And the people who believed hardest were the ones who lived longest.
  "
  }
}
```
