**Myth:**

In the age when the world was still raw and the first hands shaped clay into vessels for the dead, the **Unseen Ones** stirred. They were not born—they were *carved*, chipped from the bones of the earth by the desperate needs of the living. The people of the **First Hearths** knew only the cold, the hunt, the slow creep of starvation. Then came the **First Sign**: a hunter who dreamed of a great stag would return with meat; a woman who whispered to the river would bear twins. The Unseen Ones were not gods—they were **promises**, half-formed and hungry, feeding on the belief of those who clung to them.

The strongest promises became **Lords of the Hearth**. The **Horned One** demanded blood on the stones before the hunt; the **Weeping Mother** required tears at the birth of a child. Those who obeyed saw their fires burn brighter, their children live longer. Those who did not withered. The Lords grew in power as the tribes grew in number, their rules twisting like vines around the lives of the people. A stolen glance at a sacred fire brought sickness. A forgotten chant before battle doomed a warrior. The rituals deepened, the beliefs sharpened, until the Unseen Ones were no longer whispers—they were **laws**, carved into the bones of the earth.

The tribes that listened became **legions**. They painted their bodies with the marks of the Lords, they danced until their feet bled, they **took** what they needed from those who did not believe. Other tribes, watching, **copied**. Some were crushed for their heresy; others were absorbed, their old gods swallowed by the new. The Lords demanded **more**—more faith, more blood, more children. The world filled with their names, their rules, their **hunger**.

And the people? They did not question. They only knew this: the Lords had always been there. They had **waited**. And now, at last, they were **fed**.
